As people continue to move back to the office in 2022, it remains to be seen to what extent that will balance out with new and existing office space.I'm a little behind on this question, as the Q2 data came out in August. Given that the slightly upward trend continues, I'm lowering my forecast on bin 2 substantially. I think it would be hard for the rate to plunge from 15.1% in Q2 to 14.0% or below in 2 quarters, especially as the rate has been growing for at least the past 5 quarters, starting at 14.7%. I don't know whether such a drop would be unprecedented, but imo, it seems very unlikely for such an illiquid commodity. Similarly, a move to below 12.5% or above 17.0% would seem extremely unlikely (<0.5%), as well. Given that Q2 is at 15.1% and that the trend in the vacancy rate has been approximately +0.1% each quarter, I don't think bin 4 is completely out of the question, but it would seem very unlikely, too. Given the Q2 value of 15.1% and the increasing trend of ~0.1%/month for the past 5 quarters, I think bin 3 is most likely at this time.

As before, I'm still primarily wondering about the long-term repercussions of the pandemic, inflation/stagflation, the supply chain crunch, and the shipping mess on numbers of businesses and how people do business, but I'm making a cautiously slightly more optimistic forecast.

I was just in Manhattan, and all of the offices in Columbus Circle appeared to be empty on weekdays. The city has already 're-opened', but I think there are just a LOT of businesses whose leases haven't ended yet. Since this question is running another 16 months, that's a lot of lease cancellations/renegotiations that will take place before conclusion.

While the rate for Q2 2021 rose at half the pace of Q1 2021 (0.5% vs 1.0%), I think there's more room upward for the rate to run. Many businesses that survived 2020 and thus far in 2021 based on programs like PPP are facing new obstacles like supply chain issues, reluctant workers, and significantly higher energy costs. I think it's more likely than not that we haven't seen the peak yet. Even so, I do not see office space vacancies falling as quickly as they rose like we saw with unemployment. Looking back at 2016 - 2019, the quarterly increments were all 0.0%, 0.1%, or 0.2%. When the rate begins its descent, we aren't likely to see it in moves of 50 bps or more like we have on the ascent.

I agree with the helpful comments from @belikewater [1] and his general trends (likely climbing somewhat from here, before falling back next year). I would only add the historical perspective that 11.4% in Q4 2019 was a record low [2]. I generally expect rates to be close to 14%, with odds roughly balanced between above and below that. Possible risk is to the upside, due to increased trends towards remote work influencing renewals, and possible economic slowdown. But difficult to predict so far out.

The vacancy rate has increased each quarter since the pandemic started: 2019 Q4: 11.4% 2020 Q1: 11.5%, +0.1% 2020 Q2: 11.9%, +0.4% 2020 Q3: 12.6%, +0.7% 2020 Q4: 13.2%, +0.6% 2021 Q1: 14.2%, +1.0% 2021 Q2: 14.7%, +0.5% 6 more quarters to go in the forecast. I suspect available office space will start to match supply more closely again within a small number of quarters, as people start to go back to the office more. So I will cast my net widely, anticipating a bit of an additional increase followed by a decline. Perhaps the vacancy rate in 2022 Q2 will be similar to the vacancy rate in 2021 Q2, after a rise (to as high as ~17% in Q1 2022) and fall, and vacancy rates may continue to decline further at that point. Watch and wait.
